etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in American Antiquarian. From classical Latin superesse to be higher (than), to be on top (of), to be superior (to), to be superfluous (to), to be in excess (of a number), to remain as a residue, be left over, to remain alive, survive (from super- + esse to be) + -ive, probably after adessive, adessive

definitions: Of, relating to, or designating a case or grammatical relation used in some languages to express position above or on top of.
The superessive case; a word, form, etc., in this case.
